<h4 id="user-hostile">USER-HOSTILE</h4>

<p><strong>You coined this term in one of your articles, and Iâ€™ve loved it. Iâ€™ve heard other people talk about it, but Iâ€™d love to hear your thoughts on the user-hostile web. What would you say user-hostile is?</strong></p>

<p>The start of all this is a rather naive thought, but then it goes into something thatâ€™s a bit more interesting. The naive thought is to say, the history of the web and also the internet with other protocols was essentially to get people together and to share things. It had background in the academic world and, of course, in the military world. And then, initially, it was share thoughts. Then you had usernets. Also, letâ€™s share ideas. Thereâ€™s this basic notion that it allows a level of communication and what I like to call cross-planetary communication that was not possible, neither at that rate nor at that scale with that many people. So in so many ways, it was quite insane what it afforded.</p>

<p>That was something that naively because it wasnâ€™t all roses was something that allowed us to connect and share thoughts and ideas in a way that was not possible. So it enabled humanity to do something. And over time, of course, we created new protocols, we created email. Of course, the web itself came in in â€˜92, and then you had a lot of other services came in, right?</p>

<p>And with the dot-com boom in the 2000s, thatâ€™s when we started the business aspect of it, because there was so much money involved, and there was so much money injected into the system. That caused a change, and thereâ€™s this notion of: how do we get the most number of users, and how do we make it initially not even profitable, it was just market share because there was just so much money. And that corrupts the system a little bit, because then the incentives started changing.</p>

<p>And then it became, how can we own more of the market? Thatâ€™s a shift in thinking that takes us away from the original spirit of the web. Even in its ideals when it was created, the web was very idealistic. It wasnâ€™t about taking over, the web never said, letâ€™s take over <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gopher_(protocol)">Gopher</a> letâ€™s kill Gopher. That wasnâ€™t the idea. It was about enabling more people to get together.</p>

<p>So user-hostile for me is when the goals and the incentives of the system are not aligned with the goals and the intentions of the users. And even further, I would argue they go against the goals of the user. Because I donâ€™t think most users, if they really realized, want to be angry with their neighbors, want to be constantly scared, or constantly get the notion that someoneâ€™s out to get them, or constantly bombarded with news or thoughts that cause stress and anxiety. I donâ€™t think these are user interests, but this is how they prosper. So this is, to me, user-hostile.</p>

<p>Thereâ€™s another element to this: surveillance capitalism, which is user-hostile in the sense that we started seeing users as a means to monetizing money. Itâ€™s so normal now that even when I work with companies building websites, the marketing departments say, â€œLetâ€™s just collect the data and see what to do with it.â€ The implications of that data collection arenâ€™t really obvious. Itâ€™s improved with <a href="https://gdpr.eu/what-is-gdpr/">GDPR</a> in Europe, but still not clear.</p>

<p>We look at users as marketing touchpoints. That doesnâ€™t help. It dehumanizes usersâ€”because in the end, they are users.</p>

<p><strong>Yeah, I totally see it the same way. Thatâ€™s actually one of the reasons weâ€™re doing these interviews everyoneâ€™s chasing SEO, buying content, playing the algorithms. But we just want to create something real, talk directly to people, and not worry about gatekeepers. Itâ€™s wild how much weâ€™ve let these systems come between real relationships. Like you said, if my business doesnâ€™t work without Google, thatâ€™s not a good thing.</strong></p>

